RbNO$_{3}$ takes on four distinct phases with increasing temperature (Shamsuzzoha, 1988): \begin{itemize} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_hP45_144_3a_9a_3a-001}{Phase IV, presented here, is the ground state}, stable up to 437K. \item Phase III, stable in the range 437-492K, is in \href{current_web_home_dir/A8B24C_cP33_207_g_k_a-001}{a disordered cubic structure}, where the NO$_{3}$ ions are centered on the halide site in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_cP2_221_a_b-002}{cesium chloride ($B2)$ structure}. \item Phase II, stable up to 564K, is possibly a body-centered cubic structure with up to eight formula units in the conventional unit cell. \item Phase I, stable up to the melting point, is thought to be a \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_cF8_225_a_b-001}{sodium chloride ($B1$) structure}, with NO$_{3}$ again playing the role of chlorine. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 The phase IV structure also exists in the enantiomorphic space group $P3_{2}$ \#145. (Shamsuzzoha, 1982)
 We used the data taken at room temperature, 298K.
